Assembly statistics

Filtering

First, lets start by some statistics about assemblies and assembly filtering. The raw assemblies are polished through either arrow or quiver. We have then filtered our polished assemblies based on the coverage: contigs with too high coverage (possibly artifacts due to spurious assemblies of repeats) and too low coverage (in which the quality might be too low) have been removed.

#Gathering raw polished assembly statistics
for (sample in our_samples) {
  file_name = list.files(ASpolished_dir, 
             pattern = paste0(AS_stat_file_prefix, 
                               sample, "*"))[1]
  
  predictions = read_delim(paste0(ASpolished_dir, file_name), ":",
                         skip = 1, 
                         col_names = FALSE)
  predictions$X2 = trimws(predictions$X2, which = "both")
  colnames(predictions) = c("Statistic", sample)
  
  if (sample == our_samples[[1]]) { 
    results = predictions 
  }
  else { 
    results = full_join(results, predictions)}
}
results$Assembly_type = "Polished"


#Gathering post-filtering assembly statistics
for (sample in our_samples) {
file_name = list.files(ASfiltered_dir, 
           pattern = paste0(AS_stat_file_prefix, 
                             sample, "*"))[1]

predictions$X2 = trimws(predictions$X2, which = "both")

  results2 = predictions

}

#Putting everything together!

Orthologs

In order to identify the different orthologs in the different genomes, we have used the software PoFF, which is based on the Proteinortho tool. Proteinortho implements a version of the reciprocal best alignment, adapted to use on large datasets. PoFF builds on these results to include synteny information in a systematic way, which leads to improvement of orthologs detection in closely related genomes. Because we know that synteny is quite conserved between our genomes, we can use this method and expect improvement over not taking this layer of information into account. This seemed confirmed by our comparison of the results of PoFF and OrthoFinder, which created many large families, instead of identifying orthologs more finely.

Inter-specific comparison

First, we will define which orthologs are found only in some groups: only in Zymoseptoria genomes, only in Z. tritici genomes or only in some strains. The meaning of this last category is different for Z. tritici and for the other Zymoseptoria species. Because there is only one strain for the other Zymoseptoria species, the genes which are specific to these strains cant be distinguished from the species-specific genes. We considered these genes as belonging to the species-specific category.

get_strain_name = function(x) {
  if (x[["Species"]] == 1) {
    index = which(x[c(4:11)] != "*")
    return(strain_names[index])
  } else {return('False')}
}

Enrichment analysis per contig

Now, that we have an idea about the amount of genes belonging to these specificity levels, we wanted to know if some contigs were enriched in highly specific genes (i.e.strain or species specific). This is especially relevant in Zymoseptoria since Z. tritici is well known to be compartmentalized with distinct accessory chromosomes and core chromosomes. Note that, as previously mentioned, there are several isolates of Z. tritici (Zt09, Zt05 and Zt10) but only one of the other species. This explain the higher number of calculations done below for the Z. tritici strains.

n_simulations = 1000

#Function to compare the observed values to the randomly simulated values
count_low_high = function(x, y, z){
  if (y == "Higher"){
    return (sum(as.numeric(x[c(3:z)]) > as.numeric(x[2])))}
  else if (y == "Lower") {
   return (sum(as.numeric(x[c(3:z)]) < as.numeric(x[2])))} 
  else if (y == "Equal") {
    return (sum(as.numeric(x[c(3:z)]) == as.numeric(x[2])))}
  }

#For all samples, we gather the observed data
for (sample in samples){
  print(sample)
if (sample == "Zt09") {
  temp = ortho %>%
  filter((!!as.name(sample)) != "*") %>% 
  separate(sample, sep = "_", into = c("Sample", "Contig_name", "Gene_nb")) %>%
  mutate(Contig = paste0("Zt09_", Contig_name))
} else {
temp = ortho %>%
  filter((!!as.name(sample)) != "*") %>% 
  separate(sample, sep = "\\.", into = c("Contig", "Gene_nb"))  }
  
table_enrichment  = as.data.frame(table(temp %>% 
               filter(Specific_strain == sample) %>%
               select(Contig)))
  
colnames(table_enrichment) = c("Contig", "Observed_count")
 
#Time for the random simulations
for (i in c(1:n_simulations)) {
temp2 <- transform( temp, Specific_strain = base::sample(Specific_strain) )
sim = as.data.frame(table(temp2 %>% 
               filter(Specific_strain == sample) %>%
               select(Contig)))
colnames(sim) = c("Contig", paste0("Simulated_count_", i))
table_enrichment = full_join(table_enrichment, sim, by = "Contig") 
}

table_enrichment[is.na(table_enrichment)] = 0

until = ncol(table_enrichment)
table_enrichment$Higher =apply(table_enrichment, 1, function(x) count_low_high(x, "Higher", until))
table_enrichment$Equal =apply(table_enrichment, 1, function(x) count_low_high(x, "Equal", until))
table_enrichment$Lower =apply(table_enrichment, 1, function(x) count_low_high(x, "Lower", until))

table_enrichment %>% select(Contig, Observed_count, Higher, Equal, Lower) %>%
  write_tsv(path = paste0(specificity_output_dir, 
                          sample, "_strain_specific_per_chr.tsv"))
}

Functionnal annotations

Custom pipeline: cellular location, secretion and effectors

Workflow for functionnal annotations. The bubbles outlined in blue represent the steps which are included in our custom pipelines: we have created scripts which allow all of these steps to be launched using the predicted genes and the assembled genome with only one command line. The bubbles outlined in black are predictions steps which we ran but which are not included in our automatic pipeline. The software used for each prediction step are indicated in the bubbles.

Here, the tables resulting from our custom pipeline (outlined in blue in the figure) are parsed in order to extract the information necessary to create the figures. In the following chunk, I gather the numbers of predictions per sample for:

  • secreted proteins
  • effectors
  • genes included in metabolite gene clusters

The count of predicted effectors and genes belonging to a secondary metabolite gene cluster are straightforward and just extracted from the table. In order to define whether a gene product is expected to be secreted, however, we look at several columns and conditions:

  • a secretion peptide must have been predicted
  • the predicted cellular location must be extracellular
  • no transmembrane domain must be identified in the sequence

From the same files, I also gather the cellular location predictions.

results=list()

for (sample in samples_out) {

  #Import table with predictions from the pipeline 
  prediction_files = list.files(Annot_dir, 
             pattern = paste0(sample, "_*"))
  prediction_file = prediction_files[grepl(pattern = predictions_file_suffix, 
                              x = prediction_files, fixed = TRUE)]
  predictions = read_tsv(paste0(Annot_dir, prediction_file),
                         na = c("", "NA", "-"), guess_max = 10000)
  predictions$Sample = sample
  
  #Import table containing info about contig and position of genes
  bed_files = list.files(Annot_dir, 
             pattern = paste0(sample, "_*"))
    
  bed_file = bed_files[grepl(pattern = bed_file_suffix, 
                              x = bed_files, fixed = TRUE)]
    
  bed_table = read_tsv(paste0(Annot_dir, bed_file), col_names = FALSE)[,c(4, 1, 2, 3, 6)]
  colnames(bed_table) = c("#Protein_ID", "Contig", "Start", "End", "Strand")
  bed_table$Contig = gsub('contig_', "", bed_table$Contig)
  
  
  results[[sample]] = as.data.frame(full_join(bed_table, predictions, by="#Protein_ID"))

}

                 "Effectors" = temp_effectors, "MGC" = temp_cluster)
  
  #Additionnally, the cell compartments predicted for the gene products are

  Cell_localization$Sample = sample
  large_table_cell_loc[[sample]] = Cell_localization

CAZyme detection

In addition to our pipeline, we ran the online prediction tool dbCAN2 on all genomes in order to detect carbohydrate-active enzyme or CAZYmes. There is evidence that, in fungi, some CAZymes have a role in degrading plant cell walls and that they play a role in pathogenicity (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2997016/). The CAZymes are divided in different families. Among them, the CE (carbohydrate esterases), GH (glycosyl transferases), and PL (polysaccharide lyases) families in particular are often known as cell wall degrading enzymes (CWDEs) or plant cell call degrading enzymes (PCWDE).

get_most_frequent = function(x) {
  temp = sort(table(x),decreasing=TRUE)
  if (length(temp) == 1) {
    return(names(temp))
  } else if (temp[1] == 1) {
    return("NA")
  }
  else if (temp[1] > temp[2]) {
   return(names(temp[1]))}
  else {
    return(paste(names(temp[1]), names(temp[2]), sep = ", "))
  }
}

CAZymes$CAZyme_family = apply(CAZymes[,c(2:6)], 1, function(x) get_most_frequent(x))

for (sample in our_samples) {
  out_effectors = paste0(out_dir, "Zt09_vs_", sample, "_pacbio_for_Circos.highlights")
  out_links = paste0(out_dir, "Zt09_vs_", sample, "_pacbio_for_Circos.links")
  out_contigs = paste0(out_dir, "Zt09_vs_", sample, "_pacbio_for_Circos.contigs")
  Zt_tab = large_table %>% filter(Sample == sample) 
  
  
  #Effectors
  Zt_effectors = Zt_tab %>% filter(Effector == "Effector") %>%
    select(Contig, Start, End) 
  
  bind_rows(ref_effectors, Zt_effectors) %>%
    write_delim(path = out_effectors, delim = " ", col_names = FALSE)
  
  
  #Links for genes (accessory and cores chromosomes are not sampled in the same density due to different gene densities)
  links = inner_join(ref_tab, Zt_tab, by = c("Orthogroup")) 
  links_accessory = links[seq(1, nrow(links), 2), ] %>% 
              separate(Contig.x, into = c("Ref_name", "contig_type", "Nb"), 
                                  remove = FALSE, sep = "_", convert = TRUE) %>%
              filter(Nb >= 14)
  links_core = links[seq(1, nrow(links), 10), ] %>% 
              separate(Contig.x, into = c("Ref_name", "contig_type", "Nb"), 
                                  remove = FALSE, sep = "_", convert = TRUE) %>%
              filter(Nb < 14)

  links_to_write = bind_rows(links_accessory, links_core) %>%
    select(Contig.x, Start.x, End.x, Contig.y, Start.y, End.y)
  
  write_delim(x = links_to_write,
            path = out_links, delim = " ", col_names = FALSE)
  
  write(paste(unique(x = links$Contig.y), collapse = ';'), out_contigs)

}
